text:
<@U057C75RYBB> <@U0578M93BPE> <@U056Y707Y14>  - So I started this process but will need help from this team to finish: <https://docs.google.com/document/d/1X8wrphh_dXzGTJp5M-wyDbb38bmoTejLuDOvu-rDUZU/edit|Project Proposal>

*For context:* Based on Melinda's comments, we needed to rethink how we have features assigned and detailed.

As I understand it based on the feedback left in the document and the example proposal *here is what needs to happen:* 

1. Our breakdown of features was too granular and we need to bring these back up a level. _(thinking about what is the user able to do vs. what specific items we are implementing to make it happen)_ *So here is where I stopped:*
    a. I started to do this, see the list labeled "Full Feature List (REVISED)" and there are currently only 6 features now, which is not enough. 
    b. *What am I missing?* 
    c. *And if nothing, we need to figure out what to add to give us each 4 features to own -- which brings us to #2.*
2. Secondly, it is mandatory that *we each have to own 1 of the* *4 Base features, not just any 4 features*. 
    a. I think this is easy enough to divvy up as there are front and backend components to all of them. I made suggestions via comments under the full feature list.
    b. Also just because someone "owns" something doesn't mean they are solely responsible for delivering it. 
That all said, I think we can keep working but wanted to flag this as outstanding. Melinda gave us a *deadline of 9am 12/11 to have this revised.*

I was sent this.
Ahead of that, we have also used this explanation for project in the past that may help clear up some additional confusion:

*What is a feature?*
A feature in a web application is a non-trivial, finished piece of functionality that enhances the user experience. Features are what sets your app apart from your competitors and should add value to your application in some way. Some features are significant elements that you must have in your app that are industry standards. For example, mobile-interface is less an option and more a requirement when you consider that<https://www.oberlo.com/statistics/mobile-internet-traffic| over 58%> of web traffic comes from mobile and smartphones. Other examples of features may include the ability to send messages between users, consume an API to show current weather conditions, or the ability to pin a location on a map.

Also Lexi B is going to stop by our group tomorrow so we can discuss whatever is hanging us up.
